				\begin{document}$${V}_{{{{detach}}}}\propto {g}^{-1.5}$$\end{document}

Electrolysis was carried out both galvanostatically and potentiostatically with a three-electrode system to investigate the impact of gravity on an oxygen-evolving working electrode. 5 M sulfuric acid (titration grade, VWR Chemicals), anhydrous copper sulfate (98%, Alfa Aesar), and HPLC grade water were used to prepare both electrolyte solutions (total volume of 69 mL). The cathodic electrolyte (32 mL) consisted of copper sulfate (1.135 M) in dilute sulfuric acid (0.75 M), while the anodic electrolyte (37 mL) was dilute sulfuric acid (0.75 M). The anodic and cathodic reactions are given by Eqs. (7) and (8), respectively. Copper sulfate was chosen for the cathodic electrolyte to suppress hydrogen production on the aircraft (necessary for regulatory reasons); the anodic electrolyte was free from copper sulfate for improved electrode preservation and observation.7Anode:2H2O→4H++4e−+O2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
